reply.author: Kony Qiu
reply.text: China has established a complete industrial system, and it is difficult to strike a balance between industrial development and pollution. However, the Chinese government has adopted very tough measures to limit the emissions of factories, and even made some small factories fail because they cannot effectively control their emissions and cannot pass environmental protection assessments. In addition, the Chinese government also mandates that companies in China must purchase labor insurance for employees, so in recent years China's industrial costs have gradually increased. Some foreign companies, even Chinese companies themselves, will consider setting up factories in Southeast Asian countries with lower costs. However, China has a complete industrial system, which is still China's advantage over Southeast Asian countries.\nRegarding Beijing's pollution situation, it is actually due to Beijing's geographical environment and historical reasons. . . This history goes back to before the founding of the People's Republic of China.

author: Zac Lang
text: China and India are 10% of the world's land - but in terms of greening you can discount about about a third of all the rest, because places like the vast Sahara (9.2 million sq km.), the bulk of the middle east, half of Australia, and all of Antarctica (14.2 million sq km) can never be green, so once you mathematically factor out those, you'll see that the greening of China/India is about the same as most other places (ie Europe and the Americas). Global greening is mainly caused by increased C02 in the atmosphere. The population of India grows by 20 million every year - to put that into context, that's an extra New Delhi's worth of people every year - or the equivalent of the total populations of New Zealand, Portugal and Ireland .... every year!  If an hypothetical civil war raged in India that had the same monthly casualty rate as WW2 and WW1 (combined) - the population of India would still have an annual increase despite the death toll. India presents a huge ecological problem for itself and its neighbours within the next 100 years -

reply.author: Richard Aw
reply.text: Sorry to burst your bubble but it's not really trees, the video mainly mentions about intensive agriculture. ( own opinion : I do not consider plants/vegetation that will be harvested by removing the entire plant as a making the world greener as it is only temporary. Example: Rice, wheat or corn where the plant is removed entirely for easier harvest) It's intensive agriculture which causes greater problems in the long run and contributes greatly to global warming. Even if they do plant trees for agricultural use, it will then be chopped down after reaching maturity to provide timber, food and fuel in exchange for profit. Not to say that there aren't trees planted in hopes of saving the world from global warming. Real greenery should not be temporary.

reply.author: Richard Aw
reply.text: @Saajan Murali That is if the land is as fertile as you say and is able to sustain multiple harvests without rest and with no added chemical fertiliser to revitalise the soil. Excessive use of nitrogen-based fertilisers in agriculture is contributing to nitrous oxide emissions which is a greenhouse gas and causes global warming. Intensive agriculture also makes use of large amounts of pesticides so as to increase crop yield. Agriculture itself isn't a problem but intensive agriculture causes damage to the fertile soil and the surrounding water bodies. There are also sustainable intensive agriculture (which I support) but since the video did not state that is it sustainable, I will have to infer differently.

reply.author: Richard Aw
reply.text: @Saajan Murali (Just some extra food for thought, not concerning anything that we have talked about) If this video was about intensive animal farming, everyone in the comment or at least 50% will be criticising about how the animals are treated and the medicines used on the animals to prolong their lifespan and to speed up growth so that they can successfully reach adulthood to be slaughtered. If we applied the same logic of harvesting trees/plants and replant them again since they can grow, animals give birth which replenish their population. So why is intensive agriculture treated differently from intensive (animal) farming? Just something for everyone to think about and no I am not vegan I eat meat.\nI am just trying to understand why so many people are praising the video just because of (my assumption) the word "Greener".

reply.author: Richard Aw
reply.text: @Saajan Murali Just to add on, the last paragraph of the video's description already mentioned that it is a serious issue and that the so-called "greenery" that is the size of the amazon forest is unable to offset the damage that is already done.

reply.author: Saajan Murali
reply.text: Richard Aw I am not a great fan of intensive agriculture either considering the summa tube effects that it causes environmentally and socially, having said that ; it doesn‚Äôt disqualify for greenery is exactly my point. Also there is no rest period , I don‚Äôt know the rest of the world but in India agriculture is mature and they rotate with crops that can return nutrition to the land, atleast produce animal feed but never resting.

reply.author: Saajan Murali

I do not remember typing/saying that India's forest coverage has dropped in percentage but of the misrepresented facts in the video and the lumping of intensive agriculture under "greenery". (I am not saying that crops aren't considered greenery) . I consider crops as "temporary greenery" where they can be harvest at whim and are different from trees and forested areas. It is like planting potted plants at home and saying that you are doing reforestation, no offence. I also understand that forest cover percentage has risen over the years for a number of countries including India but as the last paragraph of the video description states, it is not enough to cover up the damage that we humans have caused.
